# What is a Switch Statement?

The **switch statement** is a decision-making statement that selects one block of code to execute from multiple possible options based on the value of an expression.

It is mainly used when there are **fixed choices**.

---

# Why Do We Need Switch?

Using multiple `if-else` statements for fixed choices makes the program lengthy and difficult to read.

The `switch` statement makes the code cleaner and easier to maintain.

Example

Instead of

```java
if(day == 1){
    System.out.println("Monday");
}
else if(day == 2){
    System.out.println("Tuesday");
}
else if(day == 3){
    System.out.println("Wednesday");
}
```

We can write

```java
switch(day){

    case 1:
        System.out.println("Monday");
        break;

    case 2:
        System.out.println("Tuesday");
        break;

    case 3:
        System.out.println("Wednesday");
        break;

    default:
        System.out.println("Invalid Day");
}
```

---

# Syntax

```java
switch(expression){

    case value1:
        // statements
        break;

    case value2:
        // statements
        break;

    default:
        // statements
}
```

---

# Components of Switch

## switch(expression)

The expression is evaluated only once.

Example

```java
switch(day)
```

---

## case

Each case represents one possible value.

Example

```java
case 1:
```

If the expression value is `1`, this block executes.

---

## break

Terminates the switch statement after executing the matching case.

Without `break`, Java continues executing the remaining cases.

---

## default

Executes when none of the cases match.

It is similar to the `else` block in an `if-else` statement.

---

# Example

```java
int day = 2;

switch(day){

    case 1:
        System.out.println("Monday");
        break;

    case 2:
        System.out.println("Tuesday");
        break;

    case 3:
        System.out.println("Wednesday");
        break;

    default:
        System.out.println("Invalid Day");
}
```

Output

```
Tuesday
```

