# Fall-through

## Definition

Fall-through is the behavior where execution continues into the following cases because there is no `break` statement.

Example

```java
int day = 2;

switch(day){

    case 1:
        System.out.println("Monday");

    case 2:
        System.out.println("Tuesday");

    case 3:
        System.out.println("Wednesday");
}
```

Output

```
Tuesday
Wednesday
```

Reason

Since there is no `break`, execution continues to the remaining cases.

---

# Enhanced Switch (Java 14+)

Modern Java introduced the enhanced switch syntax.

Example

```java
switch(day){

    case 1 -> System.out.println("Monday");

    case 2 -> System.out.println("Tuesday");

    case 3 -> System.out.println("Wednesday");

    default -> System.out.println("Invalid");
}
```

Advantages

- Cleaner syntax
- No `break` required
- No fall-through
- Easier to read

---

# Switch vs if-else

| if-else | switch |
|----------|---------|
| Used for ranges and complex conditions | Used for fixed values |
| Supports relational operators (`>`, `<`, `>=`) | Matches exact values |
| Can become lengthy | Cleaner for multiple choices |

Examples

Use `if-else`

```java
if(marks >= 90)
```

Use `switch`

```java
switch(choice)
```

---

# Time Complexity

The switch statement checks cases until a matching case is found.

Worst-case Time Complexity

```
O(n)
```

where **n** is the number of cases.

For a small fixed number of cases, it behaves like constant time in practice.

